So, we are assuming that the individuals are i.i.d. (but there could be correlation between subgroups still).\
\

\fs30 The option \'91--bfs\'92 allows to specify which Bayes factors we want to compute. The acronym \'93abf\'94 is used to mean \'93approximated Bayes factor\'94 because the Bayes factor can\'92t be calculated analytically and therefore has to be approximated using Laplace\'92s method. This approximation is very accurate, see the article by Wen & Stephens in the Annals of Applied Statistics (2013) for more details.
\fs24 \

\fs30 Specifying \'91--bfs gen\'92 computes the \'93general\'94 BF corresponding to the consistent con- figuration using the large grid. This \'93general\'94 BF is useful in a meta-analysis setting, and fixed-effect and maximum-heterogeneity BFs are also calculated (see Wen & Stephens).
\fs24 \

\fs30 Specifying \'91--bfs sin\'92 also computes the BF for each singleton, that is for configura- tions (100), (010) and (001) if there are 3 subgroups. Also, the average of the \'93general\'94 BF and each \'93singleton\'94 BF is reported under the name \'93abf.gen.sin\'94. It corresponds to \'93BF BMAlite\'94 in Flutre et al.
